This symposium is about\ntaking perhaps one
of the most enduring\nproblems on the planet,
perhaps aside from\nclimate change,
and exposing ourselves to\nnew frames of reference
and developing new lenses\nto inform our approach
to the global and\nsystemic challenges that
produce patterns of\nsociospatial poverty.
Of course, there's been\nmuch discussion about slums.
And even the use of the word\nslums, we really deliberated.
Because the word slum has a\nlonger and more continuous
history of usage and\nreference that has perhaps
made it more enduring\nthan the more recent four,
five decade-old use of the\nword informal, which also,
in my view, sets up an\nunproductive binary sometimes,
at least from a sociospatial\nplanning and design
perspective.
And I just wanted to\nmake that point here
in the design school.
In fact, Francis\n[? linea, ?] who also taught
here, doesn't even\nuse the word slums
because he feels that's\na generalization.
He uses the word shantytowns\nand it's cultural invention
as a phenomenon.
And so I think the\nusage of these words
is something we are going to\ndeliberate to perhaps come up
with a more\nconstructive, productive,
and instrumental narrative.
I mean, you know, if you\nlook up the dictionary,
the slum is a squalid,\novercrowded, urban street,
distinctly habited, very often\nby poor people, hovel, ghetto,
shantytown favela,\nJhuggi-Jhopri, bustee,
cabbagetown, rookery--
many, many such suggestions,\nbut off the physical state
of a place, of settlement,\nits material and condition.
And of course, used as a\nverb, slumming it out--
that means spending time\nat a lower social level
than one's own through curiosity\nor a charitable purpose.
So it's used in\ndifferent contexts.
And informal, which is off\nthe record, unauthorized,
unsanctioned, confidential,\nunconfirmed, et cetera,
also has great potency.
The word slum\nclearly is directed
towards physical and material\nexistence of a habitat.
So in this context, I think\nwe must understand that cities
are a set of disparities between\nthe intentions of formal modes
of practice and their spatial\nmanifestation on the ground,
thus perhaps no one\ncategory is really adequate
to describe this phenomena\nin the world today.
You know, I often hear\nin the design school--
I'd like to share this.
Marc Angelil, who is a\nprofessor at the ETH,
once shared with me their\nbig project on Ethiopia.
And it was a project that\nwas incredibly well-funded.
And they were looking\nat informal settlements.
And so they took 20\nstudents, got a bus,
spent two days identifying\nan informal settlement,
spent eight days mapping it--
photo montage, measure drawings.
And they kept the last\nday for interviews.
Now social scientists would\nhave done exactly the opposite.
And so after they finished\ntheir incredible documentation,
in the second interview, they\ndiscovered it was actually
a formal settlement.
It only looked like\nan informal setting.
[laughter]
And so I just want to say\nthis in a design school
because the aesthetic\nquestion also
becomes a very important one.
And the baggage we carry\nof that lens of aesthetics
is also highly\nproblematic sometimes.
And I hope we can\ntogether peel away
some of these layers\nin our discussions.
So we have oscillated between\nthe word informal slums.
And like I said, in\nmy own understanding,
it encodes the\nphysical condition.
And formality is the process\nof becoming and operating.
And so if you look at\ngovernance and claims and modes
of citizenship and many\nother political questions,
informal, of course, is a much,\nmuch more productive category.
And so there is this\ncontinuing tension
that we have to somehow resolve,\nbecause they are intrinsically
linked.
And often, the discussions\naround these terms
are nonproductive\nbecause we unintendingly
inflate one or the other\nmore often and then sometimes
use them interchangeably.
We've also focused on\nslums because these spaces,
for all our three\ninstitutions involved,
challenge our usual\nnotions of housing,
land occupation processes,\nas well as urban form
and urbanism more broadly,\nversus the making and imagining
of the ideal manifestation\nthat we all aspire to,
which is to say that the formal\ncity also produces slums.
Slums really present\na compelling vision
that potentially allows\nus to better understand
the blurred lines of\ncontemporary urbanism
and the changing roles of people\nin spaces in urban societies.
In this context, an\narchitecture or urbanism
of equality in an increasingly\ninequitable economic condition
requires looking deeper to\nfind a wide range of places
to mark and commemorate\nthe cultures of those
who most often are excluded\nfrom the spaces or architecture
and urban form of global flows.
And the camera, as our keynote\nspeaker, Ranjani, has argued,
has the ability to\npenetrate those lives
in these otherwise\nmarginalized spaces which
are hard to present in any\nother abstract terms or form.
Cinema, she argues, is not\nan institutionalized medium
and thus is not taken seriously\nas a scholarly enterprise
in its form.
And it is for this\nreason that we
choose to begin our symposium\nthrough the lens of film.
Ranjani Mazumdar is a\nprofessor of cinema studies
at the School of\nArt and Aesthetics
at the Jawaharlal\nNehru Institute, JNU,
as as it's called.
Her publications focus on\nurban culture, popular cinema,
gender, and cinematic city.
She's the author of\nBombay Cinema an Archive
of the City, which\nshe did in 2007,
and co-editor of a\nforthcoming a Wiley Blackwell
Companion to Indian Cinema.
Her writings have appeared\nin anthologies as well
as journals, such as Bioscope,\nContinuum, Screen, Social
Research, Journal of Television\nand New Media, et cetera--
very widely published.
She has been a European Union\nfellow in the on Indian films
at the University of\nWestminster in London,
a fellow at the Davis Center of\nHistorical Studies at Princeton
University, a British Academy\nfellow, a fellow in Paris,
visiting faculty at the\nDepartment of Cinema Studies
at New York University, and\nseveral other such positions.
She has also worked as\na documentary filmmaker.
And her productions\ninclude Delhi Diary 2001
and the Power of the Image,\nwhich she has co-directed.
Ranjani's body of\nwork and practice
speaks about cinema's ability\nto both blur and perpetuate
the formal versus\ninformal binary
that has become a definite\nelement in the approaches
to the enduring global\nphenomenon of slums.
What can be said about the\ncomplexity of contested space,
where thousands, even\nmillions of other individuals
are staking their own claims?
How does one even begin\nto frame the issue
without simplifying it?
Perhaps cinema offers\nus a point of entry.
Cinematic creative\nprojects have the ability
to blur the boundaries\nand prevent us
from realizing concrete\nand fixed assumptions
about the world.
What if we understand the\ninformal city and the slums
that produce as the\nexpression and representation
of the unrealized aspirations\nof the formal city?
How might this lens inform our\nunderstanding of the broader
visual landscape as another\nspace where the most
extreme have-nots lack agency?
To work in the contested\nspace of slums,
we must recognize is\na political choice.
When we examine the\nrole, for example today,
of doctored videos and\nfake news items which
have played a major\nrole in fueling
the flames of our current\npolitical climate,
we recognize the\npower of the visual
to blur or sharpen boundaries\nof privilege and power.
Such a reality became\nexplicitly clear to our speaker
in recent years.
Since February, 2016,\nthe students and teachers
at the JNU university where\nRanjani is a professor
have been at the receiving\nend of extremely hostility
by the Indian National\ngovernment, the BJP.
The president of the students'\nunion, Kanhaiya Kumar,
was arrested and\ncharged with sedition
for supposedly shouting\nanti-national slogans
at an event on Kashmir.
Six other students\nwere arrested.
These events led to countrywide\nprotests, political debates
in parliament, heated\ndiscussions on issues related
to nationalism, patriotism,\nthe freedom of expression,
and the laws related to this.
Teachers say the ecosystem\nof the university,
known for its liberal views and\nculture of political activism,
is in a fragile\nstate of existence.
Teachers went on\na hunger strike.
And there have been\nall sorts of protests.
Here in most of the academy\nin the United States,
we are privileged\nand hard to imagine
that, for example, an\ninstitution like Harvard,
for example, coming under\nsome similar fire, where
our daily lives are not\nimpinged on in complicated ways.
Perhaps not-- maybe\nwe are close to that.
But when our voices\nare suppressed,
how do we keep integrity?
Can we also think\nabout and be aware
of our academic environment\nas another space
where slums are defined,\nnot by their inhabitants,
but by experts,\npractitioners, and scholars,
and what does this mean\nis something I think
we should also be aware of.
What are the\naesthetic decisions we
make as designers and\nprofessional policymakers
and academics when asked\nto represent the space
and define what we call slums?
And I think this is the\ntype of dialectic space
that we hope the\nsymposium will foster.
The keynote lecture will be\nfollowed by a discussion, which
will involve Janice Perlman\nand [? brodwyn ?] Fischer,
responding to the lecture and\nthen a discussion moderated
by Mac, George McCarthy, who\nis the president and the CEO
of the Lincoln Institute of\nLand Policy here in Cambridge,
Massachusetts.
The Lincoln Institute seeks\nto improve the quality of life
through effective use,\ntaxation, stewardship of land.
He will tell us more about\nthe institution and its work
in the coming days.
But as a short intro,\nwhat I would say
