He has long seen land\nuse policy as a means
to reach gritty goals.
He's worked for his role\nas a teacher, researcher,
and funder.
He will introduce\nthe respondents
after the keynote lecture.
And with that, I invite\nProfessor Ranjani Mazumdar
to deliver her keynote lecture\ntitled, The Cinematic Slum.
Thank you.
[applause]
Thank you very much,\nRahul, for the introduction
to the symposium\nand to my own work.
I feel honored to have got\nthis invitation to kickstart
a symposium like this.
And I hope I can provoke\nsome new types of questions
with what I have to say today.
And I will not waste much\ntime and begin immediately,
because we want to stick\nto a tight schedule.
The slum has been a visual\nforce in a number of city films
from across the world.
The use of certain geographical\nlocations in popular discourses
about crime and poverty\nhave given shape
to a diverse range\nof images that
are at once powerful,\nmythic, and disturbing.
I would like to present\ntoday an account of some
of the perceptions that\nhave fueled the imagination
of the cinematic slum.
Let me start with the discussion\nof the planetary consciousness
at work and some of\nthe literature on slums
and then trace its relationship\nto photographic and cinematic
forms.
As I will show, this planetary\nvision, often influenced
by certain kinds of\nurban plans, policies,
and academic\ndiscourses, translates
into an aerial imagination.
These aerial views are,\nhowever, constantly threatened
by an overspill of challenging\nimages that foreground
a dense slum ecology.
Whether exploitative,\nsensational,
or prone to accusations\nof poverty porn,
the range of cinematic\nimages offered
a hyper-sensory encounter\nwith the world of the slum.
These encounters rely on\ncertain techniques that
are unique to cinema\nand therefore provide
an alternative form\nof knowledge that
is different from\nsociological, historical,
and economic accounts of slums.
I hope to focus particularly\non the visceral, violent,
and embodied forms\nof experiences
that the cinematic slum\nhas become known for.
In his book, Planet\nof the Slums,
Mike Davis presents us\nwith an apocalyptic account
of a future overwhelmed\nby the expansion of slums.
Large-scale migration\nto the cities
has resulted in\ncongested spaces.
And the slum is now\na fait accompli.
While slums have been a presence\nin most cities of the world
in the second half\nof the 20th century,
the global south\nhas increasingly
witnessed a concentration\nof squatter settlements.
Davis's account is powerful.
It makes us sit up\nwith a sense of shock
and asks us to understand the\npower of statistics and data
that he parades for the reader.
The whirlwind of\nstaggering information
is meant to shake us\nout of our reverie,
to recognize a crisis that\nis at once economic, social,
political, and ecological.
The cover of the\nbook provides us
with a high angle view\nof a Brazilian favela.
A decade after the publication\nof Davis's book, Johnny Miller,
in his award-winning\nphotographic work
titled Unequal Scenes, captured\naerial views of inequality.
Miller started work\ninitially in South Africa
but soon branched\nout in 2016 to use
drones for the capture\nof striking images
from around the world.
These images provide high\nangle views of major cities,
with dense clusters of\nlow-income housing set
against the wealthier districts.
The countries where\nMiller took pictures
include South Africa, India,\nTanzania, the United States,
and Kenya.
The desire to generate\nthese high angle images
came to Miller during his time\nas an anthropology student
in South Africa.
He was struck by the tin\nshacks and their existence
right next to the\naffluent neighborhoods.
Says Miller, and I\nquote, "The images
that I find the\nmost powerful are
when the camera is looking\nstraight down what's
known as nadir view, looking\nat the actual borders
between rich and poor.
Sometimes this is a fence,\nsometimes a road or wetlands,
with small shacks of\npoor houses on one side
and larger houses or\nmansions on the other.
Whatever it is about\nthe composition
of those photographs, they are\nextremely powerful to people.
I think the images make\ninequality relevant.
People can see themselves\nreflected in the images.
And it\'s deeply\nunsettling," end of quote.
There is an uncanny\nresemblance in Davis's account
in the Planet of Slums\nand Miller's photographs
in his Unequal Scenes.
Both capture broad\ntrends in the world
and focus on scale,\nnumbers, and the desire
to instill a sense of shock.
There is something powerful in\nthis spectacle of inequality.
And it is hard to ignore it.
The issue, however, is the\ndeployment of a distanced gaze,
both in the book and\nin the photographs.
This distance is created\nby an aerial perspective,
a planetary view,\nso to speak, which
recognizes an essential\ninterconnectedness
between all humankind\nand the earth,
a relationship that transcends\nnations to foreground a shared
vision of a united humanity.
The aerial view popularized\nsince the experience of flight
is now a widespread\nform and has deeply
affected the way we understand\ngeography and territory.
While aerial photography has\nbeen constructively deployed
in the service of\nwar, cartography,
and archaeological\nsurveys, we need
to understand how\nthis form of vision
emerged so strongly as\na cultural phenomenon.
In the course of its\nhistory, the aerial view
has offered us the fantasy\nof visual possession
of vast space.
Since this form of\nlooking is distinctly
different from ground\nlevel perception,
there is a quality\nof abstraction
that comes into play in any\nhigh angle view of the world.
What we experience\nis a move away
from a complex and contradictory\nreality to an image form
where the unruly and\nthe untidy appear tidy.
This is a process where\neyesores seen at ground level
get transformed\nthrough aerial vision
into striking\nforms of spectacle.
Complex social context, lived\nrealities, and experiences
are reduced to a\nplanar spatiality
that instills a generalized\nnotion of the universal.
Davis's book has been classified\nas urban crisis writing
by Ravi Sundaram, an\napocalyptic imagination that
seems to steer clear from\nthe complexities that exist
inside the slums themselves.
Miller's photographs seem\nto carry Davis's ideas
into his striking account of\ninequality seen from above.
These descriptions,\nhowever, do not obviously
capture the concrete experiences\nof the slums' inhabitants.
As against Davis's\napocalyptic imagination,
we do also have other\nperspectives that
have documented not just\nthe concrete realities
and experiences of\nthose living in slums,
but also provided access\nto the infrastructures
of the informal economies that\noperate in these locations.
The effort in these\nmicro accounts
has been to trace patterns as\nwell as distinct differences,
to understand the diverse\ncontext of slum worlds,
the way they look,\noperate, and survive.
There are many examples\nof this kind of work.
In Shadow Cities,\nRobert Neuwirth
provides narratives of\nordinary slum dwellers.
For two years, he explored\nslums in four continents.
And despite their world\nof poverty, despair,
and political corruption,\nhe experienced a great deal
of the human spirit.
The book has a\nstrong tone of hope.
And squatters are\npresented as entrepreneurs
who cope by staying\noutside of the asphalt
world, the term used\nby them to refer
to the streets and political\nsystem of the legal city.
The book takes us to\na sense of community,
a place of friendship and bonds,\nand a highly productive life.
In some ways, these\ntwo opposing tendencies
of expressing the\nexpansive horror
of the slum\nexperience via numbers
and statistical\nclassification and the search
for a spirited community\nof residents engaged
in informal networks\nof the economy
has framed the popular dynamics\nof slum representations.
In the cinematic world,\nhowever, this narrative
becomes complicated.
Danny Boyle's Slumdog\nMillionaire, released in 2008,
became a major success across\nthe world with its rags
to riches story.
Based on a novel, the primary\nstructure of the narrative
moves between a popular\ntelevision game show,
How to be a Millionaire,\nand memories
of one of the contestants,\nJamal, a Muslim boy
who grew up in Bombay slums.
Just before the\nfinal round, when
he is about to win a\nlarge sum of money,
Jamal is picked up by the\npolice for questioning
because the host of\nthe show can't believe
a boy from the\nslum could possibly
know all the answers to the\nquestions asked in the show.
The narrative does not try to\nbe plausible or believable,
for the focus clearly was to\nfind a language with which
to convey the memory of\ngrowing up in Bombay's slums.
The film was both controversial\nas well as appealing.
There is a desire to penetrate\nthe density of Bombay's slum
world, to access sensory fabric.
Boyle deploys a cinematic\nlanguage of encounters
to explore the\nnetworks of the slum,
to narrate the stories\nof two brothers,
yet the labyrinthine\nstructure of the space
defies any easy access\nto a totalizing view.
A key issue for us here\nis that of navigation
since it is in the\nworld of cinema
that we have seen the most\nsustained desire to move
into these spaces, to\ntrade on various kinds
of spectatorial experiences of\nfear, excitement, voyeurism,
and thrill.
This is absolutely central to\nthe way the idea of the slum
has become enmeshed in our\nthinking of certain kinds
of urban spaces that we\ndo not always know well
but have only\nheard of or learned
about via a global production\nof pictures and documents, news
reporting, literature,\nand cinema.
This indeed is what makes\nthe slum iconography so
difficult to establish, since\nits so-called authentic life is
now no longer available\noutside this blitzkrieg
of visual production.
Slums are diverse\narchitecturally, socially,
in terms of infrastructure,\nand in terms
of the geographical locations\nwithin urban spaces.
They are mysterious,\nalways around
but never fully understood.
So the techniques\nused by cinema have
tended to play with the\nnature of the medium itself.
Giuliana Bruno refers to film\nas a form of modern cartography,
where we can clearly\nsee connections
between space and emotion.
Forms of mobility\ndeployed by cinema
usually take us\nacross time and space
to invoke a unique\nmap of filmic affect.
Slumdog revels in this\nkind of expressivity.
The opening sequence\nin the film uses
the chase, a popular\ndevice in cinema,
to navigate Mumbai slums.
Boyle takes us to Dharavi as the\nsite for the story to unfold.
Dharavi is one of the\nlargest slums in Asia
and houses around\n700,000 people.
It is a complex space, a\nsite of high productivity,
poor infrastructure, outsourced\nlabor, and global networks.
Within this space, many\ndifferent lives co-exist.
And not all of these stories are\ncaptured by Boyle in Slumdog,
and yet it is what\nhe captures that is
of particular\nsignificance for us
to understand how a narrative\nof embodied knowledge
is presented as a distinctly\ndifferent imagination
from the planetary\nconsciousness at work in Davis
and Miller's work.
If the high angle drone\nimagery that we have just seen
seeks to generate abstract\nspectacles of shock,
Boyle assaults our senses with\na form of visual cartography
to invoke the ecology\nof Mumbai's slums.
