The sequence starts with a\ndynamic view of an airport
track, the hazy apartment block\nskyline, the impish playfulness
of the children, to finally\nenter the streets and bylanes
of Dharavi as the children get\nchased by a police constable.
The chase is superbly\ncrafted, an energetic run
that reveals various\naspects of the space to us.
Yet this is a form\nof mapping that
foregrounds the bodily\nexperiences of the children
and their deft navigation\nacross rooftops, alleys,
water pipes, and staircases.
The constable finds it difficult\nto negotiate the space.
The children, on the other hand,\nhave a relationship of play
as Boyle edits their\nspeedy movement to music.
We see the slum as a\nspace with giant pipes,
sewage, blue-colored\nplastic floating in water,
narrow alleys, and a combination\nof tin and thatched roofs.
The two kids really\nknow their way around
as the director moves\nfrom ground level
to the high angle shot\nshowing the thatched roofs.
This play between\nthe high and the low
is interesting since up close,\nwe get a sense of the slum
as we blur through the alleys.
This is typical for\nany chase sequence,
since its attempt is always\nto capture a sensorium
and thrill of\nmovement through what
appears to be very dense space.
Through this\nopening sequence, we
are provided access to a\nform of spatial knowledge
that children possess.
A similar controversy about the\nsensational nature of the film
shadowed Fernando Meirelles's\nCity of God, released in 2002.
City of God is based\non a true story
set in 1960s Rio based\non a best selling novel
by Paulo Lins, who\ngrew up in a favela.
The narrative moves between\nthe '60s and the '80s
and follows the different\njourneys of the two
protagonists, Li'l Ze, a dreaded\nteenage gangster, and Rocket,
another teenager who wants to\nbecome a photographer to escape
the favela.
The story unfolds from the\npoint of view of Rocket.
City of God adopted a style\nthat relentlessly pummels
the spectator with\na tale of drugs,
crime, and corruption\nlocated inside the favelas.
It is intriguing how\nthe opening of the film
opens with a similar\ncartographic impulse
as Slumdog but with a\ndistinctly violent edge to it.
