The significance of\nboth these sequences
lies in their\nattempt to carve out
a mediatized imagination\nfor a discussion of slums
in a globalized world.
Both films deal with the\nmetamorphosis of childhood.
This focus on childhood is\nnot unknown in the history
of world cinema.
And yet there is something\ndifferent about films
like City of God and Slumdog.
A brief comparison\nwith certain depictions
available from an earlier era\nmay help to shed light on this.
Hector Babenco's\nPixote, released
in 1981, and Mira Nair's Salaam\nBombay, released in 1988,
are two iconic\nfilms of the 1980s.
Both films on childhood\nexperiences of poverty
were inspired by\nthe Mexican film
Los Olvidados, which translates\nas The Young and the Damned,
directed by Luis.
Bunuel in 1959.
In each of these films, the\nslum is the master narrative
that is never overtly present\nin its architectural density
but is the infrastructural\ncondition for the way
that children experience life.
Mira Nair's Salaam Bombay\ndeals with the lives
of street children.
Shot in the slums\nof Bombay, the film
shows the story of Krishna,\na 10-year-old boy who
works for a traveling\ncircus but is
abandoned when the employers\nmove away abruptly.
He then heads for\nBombay and gets
a job working as a tea boy.
The film centers on\nKrishna's daily deliveries
to a brothel and the\nassortment of characters
he meets over there.
Salaam Bombay builds on\na sentimental narrative,
with the child retaining an\nintrinsically human quality
that remains untouched\nby his circumstances.
The film refrains from\nany direct articulation
of physical aggression.
There are intimations\nof potential violence,
but we don't see them on screen.
And the desire to hold\nonto some [? originally ?]
sense of innocence\nor absolute truth
remains the dominant emotional\ntexture of the narrative.
Many critics and viewers\nhave compared Nair's venture
to Babenco's Pixote, released\nearlier in the decade.
As abandoned cast-offs,\nthe children of Pixote
live by their wits on the cruel\nstreets of Sao Paulo in Brazil.
Their survival depends on\nthe trading of sex and drugs
as the narrative takes us\nthrough a series of events
that act upon the children.
Unlike Salaam Bombay, there is\nsomething relentlessly brutal
in Pixote.
It's like being in a\nno-exit world, where not
even the cleverest of\nthe children can survive.
A sense of desperation\nruns through the narrative
with absolutely no hope\navailable for the children.
We are made to view a cataloging\nof strange atrocities, where
beauty is forever doomed\nand a sense of entrapment
emerges as the dominant emotion.
Babenco takes an ironic\napproach to the aerial view
by opening the film with a\nstraightforward introduction
to the film's context.
