While these three very\nsignificant films on childhood
are distinctly different\nin their approach,
together they offer a\nset of interventions
on the slum child's existence.
In these slice-of-life\nnarratives,
events act upon the\nchildren and their bodies.
Despite their very\ndifferent styles,
a binding element\nin the three films
is the influence of\nItalian neorealism.
Let me quickly describe\nsome of the features
of this cinematic\nstyle, which emerged
in the context of post-war\ndevastation in Italy
and soon became a global\ndebate about realism and cinema
in the decades to follow.
Where am I?
[laughs] In the\ndecades to follow--
neorealists were\ncommitted to a notion
of the everyday [inaudible].
One of its theorists,\nCesare Zavattini,
referred to it as a\ndailiness of people's lives.
The camera should just\nenter the ongoing unfolding
of reality as a guest.
Neorealists believed in\nan unconditional focus
on the present, to explore how\npeople's actions were shaped
by necessity and circumstances.
Real locations,\nstreet images, the use
of nonprofessional actors, and\nan analytical documentary style
became the chief characteristics\nof the realist mode.
There was a belief here in\nthe ontological wholeness
of the reality being filmed.
They preferred the long take\nand depth in cinematography
and did not appreciate\nthe use of montage
or any other\nstylization generated
at the post-production stage.
Nair, Bunuel, and Babenco\nused nonprofessional actors,
along with an overt use of many\nof the well-known conventions
of Italian neorealism.
The aerial view was\nironically structured
in two of these films\nwith a clear belief
that observation from an\nexternalized point of view
was perhaps the best way to\ncapture a sense of reality.
Bunuel's Los Olvidados,\nhowever, played
with surrealistic elements\nand remained unsentimental
till the end.
He was clear about\nthe role of the camera
and did not want to\nexpress some naive
discourse on authentic reality.
It is perhaps this\nfilm that in some ways
offers us the entry\npoint for a discussion
of the hypersensory drives of\nboth Slumdog and City of God.
The most significant\nelement in both films
is the movement between\npast and present
and the stylized use of\nflashbacks, techniques
that neorealism did not deploy.
In both films, the\nchildren grew up.
And the temporal play between\nchildhood and the present
offers an unusual instance\nof embodied knowledge
that is foregrounded as a\ndeep and felt experience,
yet there is no\nfixed identity that
emerges since we have\ntwo sets of characters
in each film, both\nfollowing different parts,
despite a common and\nshared experience.
They are not sociological\ntypes but subjects
who approach life differently.
