As he relays his\nanswer to the TV show,
the spectator is made\naware of the nature
of embodied experience,\nfelt and relayed as memory.
In doing this, Danny Boyle is\nprivileging the sensory world
of the slum inhabitant\nand moving away
from a realist and objectivist\naccount of life in the slums.
Both films offer descriptions\nof sites and spaces
which are conveyed through\nthe language of memory.
The recognition that\nthe catastrophes
of the past, present,\nand future are
located in the\nspaces of the city
saturates the overall\nvision of the films.
The shadow of death and\nplay creates an intersection
between memory and\nsetting, time and place.
Memory gives form\nto the city just
as the city transforms memory.
Knowing a city\nwell is linked also
to childhood, the\nability to play out
the intersections between\nchildhood impressions
and the adult's\nability to recall.
It is this interconnectedness\nof perspectives
that Walter Benjamin\nhad described so vividly
in his reflections on childhood\nas a conceptual framework
for urban memory.
The child provides\na disruptive vision
that punctures the notion\nof the adult's recall
as stable and distant.
The perception of the\nchild, in a sense,
becomes a privileged\nmode of knowing.
But it is in the fullness of\ntime and the space of adulthood
that meaning is achieved\nretrospectively.
The significance\nof the past comes
to light only in the context\nof a pressing present.
It is the complex relationship\nbetween the memory
of a particular site and the\nsite of that particular memory
that is of immense importance in\nthe narratives of urban recall.
City of God and\nSlumdog Millionaire
are unique for the\nway they operate
through these\nlandscapes of memory.
They also draw on a form\nof mediatized language,
televisual liveness, music\ntelevision, news photography,
the use of digital effects.
These intermedial elements\ncreate their own sensorium,
which some have described\nas hyper-realism.
Both Slumdog and City of\nGod adopt a multimedia
expressivity.
And it is interesting how\nthe media itself is so
crucially placed in both films.
Jamal in Slumdog is speaking\nto us through television,
while in City of\nGod, Rocket's memory
is channelized for the world\nthrough his photographs.
In City of God, the\nevents move at a pace
that becomes difficult to\nretain for the filmmaker.
There is a desire to\nrecognize the media
world and its circulation\nof popular culture,
to stage this entry\ninto slum life.
Through these intersections, the\nfilms make it clear that they
cannot transcend into a\nplanetary perspective.
Rather, life itself has\ncome to resemble the movies.
Igor Krstic, in fact, suggests a\nconnection between the gunshots
and the camera in City of God.
By drawing on a more general\ntendency of popular cinema,
particularly in popular\nmale action, horror, crime,
or gangster film\ngenres, the film
probes the ethical limits\nof representing violence
on screen.
Narrative itself\nfrays at the edges
as events bleed through\nwith great force.
I hope through the\npresentations today,
I have managed to foreground\nthe distinctly different logic
at work in the capture\nof slum life on screen.
