So I'm going to get\nstraight to the point.
As a historian of Latin\nAmerica and Brazil,
I would like to do three things\nin these quick comments--
the first is to try to place the\ninformal city that we've just
seen in these filmic\nrepresentations both
in the context of time-- to\ntake us back in time and think
a little bit about cinema\nin the early stages,
particularly in Brazil--
and also to take it to\nthe realm of other kinds
of cultural representation\nand talk a little bit
about how film is very similar\nto other ways of representing
the favela that we can\nsee in other contexts
and other spaces.
I'll then second\ngo on to talk about
what is the nature\nof the messages that
are coming from cultural\nproduction about the favela,
particularly in Brazil, but\nalso in this larger context?
And lastly, I'd like to\ntalk a little bit about what
that has meant in terms of\nthe kinds of policies that
tend to be created on the basis\nof the images and the visions
that we see in film\nand that we see
in other cultural\nrepresentations.
So it's actually\nreally a privilege
to be somebody who\nworks in Brazil
and to think about these issues,\nbecause Brazil has had places
that have been\nidentified as favelas,
as shantytowns, as informal\ncities, for almost exactly 120
years.
1898 was the date that the first\nfavela was named in Brazil.
It wasn't the first time\nthat that kind of settlement
existed.
But it was the first\ntime that it was named.
And importantly, that\nwas when it began
to be thought of as a problem.
And almost as soon as\nthat kind of neighborhood
began to be thought\nof by the elite,
by architects, by planners,\nby governors, as a problem,
then it started\nto be represented
in different kinds of media.
The first filmic representations\nof favelas in Brazil
are actually from the 1900s,\nfrom the very beginnings
of the genre of film\nin Brazil itself.
And they were not surprisingly\nrepresentations of Carnival.
Carnival came from the favelas.
And the music samba\ncame from the favelas.
And almost as soon\nas it began to make
its way into the\nstreets of Rio, you
began to have photographers\nand filmmakers
going and trying to catch\nsnippets of that live action.
You had the first\nactual lengthy film
devoted to the favela in 1926.
It was a rant\nagainst favelas that
was meant to justify\na removal campaign
by a member of the\nRotary Club and a very
important influential policy\nmaker named Mattos Pimenta.
And then in 1935, you had\nthe first long action drama,
not only that was the first\none to be set in the favela,
but a movie-- it was called\nFavela Dos Meus Amores-- that
was considered the very first\nserious dramatic national film
in Brazilian cinema.
So it wasn't only the first\nrepresentation of a favela,
but it was actually\nthought to be
the beginning of\nthe representation
of some authentic vision of\nBrazil in the cinematic realm.
And that juxtaposition\nis very important.
It isn't just a kind of external\nrepresentation of this place,
but an external representation\nof this place as something
that represents what\nBrazil is all about.
And so that's a very\ninteresting difference,
I think, between the\nfilms that we've just seen
and some of these early films.
It was followed in the 1950s\nwith two very important films
that are understood\nas the beginning
of cinematic realism in Brazil\nby Nelson Pereira dos Santos.
One of them in 1955 is\ncalled Rio 40 Graus--
so Rio 40 Degrees\nor 110 degrees--
and another one in 1957\ncalled Rio Zona Norte.
And then, of course, there's\nthe very famous Orfeu Negro
in 1959.
And this series of\nfilms is actually
the beginnings of\nthe representations
of the favela in Brazil.
And it was coincident\nwith the beginnings
of these kinds of\nrepresentations in other parts
of Latin America as well,\nalthough I don't have time
to talk about that.
One of the things that's really\ninteresting about these films
is that they mimic in\nmany ways other forms
of cultural production.
So we have, for example, in\n1903, the very first example
of a chronicler who goes\nup to the hills of Rio
and wants to expose them\nto the rest of the world,
wants to tell everybody\nwhat these places are like.
That begins in 1903.
You also have samba, which is\na kind of popular journalism.
And its material,\nits prime material
from the very\nbeginning, is to tell
outsiders what the world\nof the favela is like.
And this becomes, by the 1930s,\nBrazil's national music, right?
And so Brazil's\nnational music is
about these places, usually\nvery positive representations,
the favela as a site\nof authenticity,
of love, of community\nin this sense
of togetherness and unity.
It's also, of course,\na space of blackness.
And it's the first\ncultural medium
in which blackness is really\nportrayed in a positive light,
is through samba.
You have photographers\ngoing up in the hills
as early as the early 1900s.
And poets and novelists\nsoon followed.
There are, in 1935,\ntwo major novels
that are set in favela\ncommunities and that project
to the rest of the world what\nthese places are all about.
And then, of course, you\nhave the modernist artists
who very famously go up into\nthe hills in the 1920s and '30s
and produce not only\npaintings, but also other forms
of more abstract visual art.
And poets follow them\nup into the hills--
all of this to say that\ncinematic representations are
very old.
And they're part of a whole\nkind of cultural construct
that exists from very, very\nearly on in the history
of these kinds of settlements.
Now the second question-- what\ndoes this cultural production
tell us?
Now there's a very\nsimplistic way
of thinking about this--\nthat it can tell us
good things about the\nfavelas and bad things
about the favelas, right?
And if we were to\nthink about the movies
that we've just seen,\nthere is, of course,
a deeper level where\nwhat we're seeing
is the nature of the\nprotagonists in these films.
And I very much agree that\nthere is, in these latest
representations, a lot\nmore depth, a lot more
understanding of the meaning\nof what these places are.
But they are overwhelmingly\nnegative representations--
representations of suffering,\nof violence, of extremes.
And one of the things that's\ninteresting about Brazilian
films is that from\nthe beginning,
they're not\ncompletely about that.
In fact, the early\ngeneration of films
is much more about these\nexperiences of human emotion,
experiences of family,\nexperiences of connection,
experiences of all of the\nthings that the sambas
were telling the rest\nof the Brazilian public
that favela life was all about.
So they'll say the\nasphalt, the city,
those are the fake people.
Those are the liars.
Those are the policemen\nand the authorities
that come in to beat us up.
But we here, we have invented\nthis beautiful musical genre.
We understand what human\nfeeling is all about.
We understand that\ngreed is wrong in a way
that people down\nthere on the asphalt
who are speculating on real\nestate don't understand.
And we want you to see our\nauthentic Brazilian black life
here in the favela.
And so there's this kind\nof positive representation
that comes across in these early\nfilms that's very interesting.
Of course, there's also a lot\nof negative representation.
And films were used\nas propaganda pieces
to try to build sentiment\nagainst what were understood
to be all of the problems of\nthe space of the favela as well.
But I won't repeat that\nbecause that vision, I think,
is projected far more\nthan the positive vision
that I've just told you about.
But there's also a\ndeeper level that I just
want to spend the\nvery few minutes
that I have left explaining.
And that is that\nwhether these films
and these other\ncultural expressions
were positive or\nnegative, whether they
saw beautiful blackness\nor whether they
saw degenerate, racialized\nideas of misery and marginality,
no matter which side\nof that they fell on,
there are certain\ncommonalities in all
of these representations.
And to put this in\nvery few words, what
it is that they're\nseeing in the favela
is a space that is separate,\na space that is enclosed,
and a space that\nis fundamentally
understood as other when you\ncompare it to the asphalt, when
you compare it to the city.
You can even see that it\nLos Olvidados in that clip
that we just saw this idea that\nyou have these modern cities.
And then you have\nthese other spaces.
And the other spaces are\nin some ways timeless.
They don't belong to modernity.
They don't belong to what the\nrest of the city is about.
So there's this separation.
There's also this idea in\nall of these cultural mediums
that you need a\ncultural guide, that you
need some kind of intermediary\nthat's going to take you--
and this is from 1903 on.
They actually say it outright.
You can't go up to the\nfavela by yourself.
You need someone to take you\nand explain to you what is what,
because you're not going to be\nable to navigate these alleys.
You're not going to\nbe able to understand.
So whether the guide is\nthe chicken in City of God
