to the rest of the city,
but these are also\nspaces that serve
a function within the systems\nof economic inequality
and also the systems\nof power relationships
that govern the city as a whole.
That is, these are not places\nthat are there by accident.
But they are places\nthat actually
have a place in larger\nstructures of power,
larger structures\nof inequality, that
are the actual roots\nof the problem.
It's not what happens within\nthe favelas borders that
causes whatever aspects of\nfavela life result in suffering
or are problematic.
The problem is actually\nin that relationship
between those spaces and these\nlarger structures of power.
And cultural\nrepresentations tend
to downplay that by focusing\non the favelas as spaces apart,
as spaces that deserve to be\nfocused on without reference
to what's going on around them.
And I think that's\nsomething that we can really
take forward, I hope, in\nthe next couple of days
of discussions at\nthis conference.
